<h2>Frequently Asked Questions for South Carolina Workers</h2>

<h3>What withholding form does South Carolina use?</h3>
<p>South Carolina uses Form SC W-4 (South Carolina Employee's Withholding Allowance Certificate). You submit this to your employer when you start work or when you want to change your withholding. South Carolina's SC W-4 is similar in structure to the federal W-4, allowing you to claim allowances or additional withholding. If you have not filed an SC W-4, your employer typically withholds at the default rate. The SC W-4 is available from the South Carolina Department of Revenue website and should be updated whenever your personal tax situation changes (marriage, new dependents, etc.).</p>

<h3>South Carolina's rate is going down each year. Which rate should I use for stubs?</h3>
<p>Use the rate applicable to the pay period you are documenting. For pay periods in 2024, the top rate is 6.4%. For 2025, it should reduce further (check the South Carolina Department of Revenue for the confirmed rate each year, as reductions depend on state revenue performance). When generating stubs for current income verification purposes, use the current year's applicable rate. The annual rate changes are relatively small (0.1% increments), so the impact on individual stubs is minor -- a few dollars per paycheck -- but accuracy matters when lenders or landlords are reviewing detailed documentation.</p>

<h3>I work at BMW in Spartanburg on rotating shifts. Does my pay stub look different?</h3>
<p>BMW Spartanburg workers on rotating production shifts typically receive shift differentials for second and third shifts, which appear as additional pay categories on formal pay stubs. Overtime during high-production runs is also common. When documenting your income, capture the actual gross pay for each pay period including base wages, shift differentials, overtime, and any production bonuses. For mortgage applications, lenders often average your last 24 months of earnings to determine qualifying income, which smooths out the variation between high-overtime and low-overtime periods. Our <a href="/hourly-pay-stub-template">hourly pay stub template</a> shows how to structure documentation when multiple pay rates appear in a single pay period.</p>

<h3>Does South Carolina have any state payroll deductions beyond income tax?</h3>
<p>No. South Carolina has no state disability insurance, no state paid family leave program, and no additional mandatory employee payroll deductions beyond the graduated state income tax. Your South Carolina pay stub deductions are: state income tax (up to 6.4%), federal income tax, Social Security (6.2%), and Medicare (1.45%), plus any voluntary deductions you elect (health insurance, 401(k), etc.). This keeps South Carolina's payroll structure simple compared to states like California or New Jersey with multiple state-mandated insurance programs.</p>

<h3>I'm a seasonal worker in Myrtle Beach. How do I document income for an apartment application?</h3>
<p>Seasonal workers face the challenge of showing landlords that their summer income is real and repeatable, even if their off-season income is lower. The most effective approach is to generate stubs for each pay period across an entire year, showing the full income cycle honestly. Many Myrtle Beach landlords who rent to seasonal workers are familiar with the pattern and evaluate annual income rather than just current-month earnings. If you have two or more years of tax returns showing consistent seasonal earnings, those are the strongest documentation. Generated stubs should match your actual deposits -- if you receive weekly pay from a hotel or resort, generate weekly stubs that match your bank records. See our <a href="/pay-stub-for-apartment">pay stub for apartment applications</a> guide for what property managers typically require.</p>

